00:02:55.890 --> 00:02:59.000
But since we don't
have a lot of time,

00:02:59.000 --> 00:03:01.600
I'll just will move forward.

00:03:01.600 --> 00:03:05.080
Anybody know who this-- why
this individual is important,

00:03:05.080 --> 00:03:06.860
Dr. Carter G. Woodson?

00:03:06.860 --> 00:03:07.680
What is his role?

00:03:07.680 --> 00:03:08.790
What is his contribution?

00:03:08.790 --> 00:03:11.660
Why would I want to
dedicate this presentation

00:03:11.660 --> 00:03:13.530
to Dr. Woodson.

00:03:13.530 --> 00:03:15.090
OK, let me help you out.

00:03:15.090 --> 00:03:16.940
He's a founder of
what we now call

00:03:16.940 --> 00:03:19.800
African Heritage Month,
or Black History month.

00:03:19.800 --> 00:03:24.920
He found, what was then called
Negro History Week, in 1926

00:03:24.920 --> 00:03:28.570
because he said that the
contributions by people

00:03:28.570 --> 00:03:33.530
of African descent really is a
part of US and world history,

00:03:33.530 --> 00:03:34.880
yet these are the missing pages.

00:03:34.880 --> 00:03:37.760
And Dr. Woodson
though, back in 1926,

00:03:37.760 --> 00:03:41.350
that it would mean a lot if
we included these pages back

00:03:41.350 --> 00:03:42.695
into the historical text.

00:03:42.695 --> 00:03:46.550
And he's one of the greatest
historians of our time.

00:03:46.550 --> 00:03:47.830
He's done quite a lot.

00:03:47.830 --> 00:03:52.880
I mean he's wrote more than
a dozen books, Dr. Woodson.

00:03:52.880 --> 00:03:55.310
His organization,
The Association

00:03:55.310 --> 00:03:58.180
for the Study of African
American Life and History,

00:03:58.180 --> 00:04:01.670
founded in 1915, is
still the leading

00:04:01.670 --> 00:04:04.870
African American historical
organization in the country.

00:04:04.870 --> 00:04:11.320
Every year, they have
an annual convention.

00:04:11.320 --> 00:04:13.467
And the Journal of Negro
History has been updated.

00:04:13.467 --> 00:04:15.550
Now, it's the Journal of
African American history.

00:04:15.550 --> 00:04:18.120
It's the leading
journal in the country.

00:04:18.120 --> 00:04:20.649
So we know Woodson quite a lot.

00:04:20.649 --> 00:04:24.220
And he founded the occasion
more than 88 years ago.

00:04:24.220 --> 00:04:27.750
And there was a
stamp in his honor.

00:04:27.750 --> 00:04:30.890
And one of his classic books,
he's wrote more than a dozen,

00:04:30.890 --> 00:04:33.090
on the miseducation
of Negroes and really

00:04:33.090 --> 00:04:34.600
focuses on the
American education

00:04:34.600 --> 00:04:38.240
system that really leaves
out students of color,

00:04:38.240 --> 00:04:40.850
in particular people
of African descent,

00:04:40.850 --> 00:04:44.130
from their own
contributions to the world.

00:04:44.130 --> 00:04:46.310
And so he's one of the great
historians of our time.

00:04:46.310 --> 00:04:50.570
So now, you all know
the great Dr. Woodson.

00:04:50.570 --> 00:04:54.120
And moving forward--
well, I won't

00:04:54.120 --> 00:04:57.740
to focus on northeast
Africa and contributions

00:04:57.740 --> 00:05:00.427
mainly from ancient Egypt.

00:05:00.427 --> 00:05:02.260
And as you can see,
this is a map of Africa.

00:05:02.260 --> 00:05:05.560
And I was there last
year, and I can assure you

00:05:05.560 --> 00:05:08.130
that Egypt did not
detach itself from Africa

00:05:08.130 --> 00:05:10.500
and float off to
the Middle East.

00:05:10.500 --> 00:05:11.250
I double checked.

00:05:11.250 --> 00:05:12.330
I triple checked.

00:05:12.330 --> 00:05:15.020
And when I was in Egypt,
I was on African soil.

00:05:15.020 --> 00:05:17.470
So it's still part of
the African continent,

00:05:17.470 --> 00:05:20.250
even today, even thought it's
not really taught that way.

00:05:20.250 --> 00:05:21.680
So this is the area here.

00:05:21.680 --> 00:05:24.870
So I've done research in
different parts of the world,

00:05:24.870 --> 00:05:27.170
but today, I'll focus
mainly on Egypt.

00:05:27.170 --> 00:05:29.490
But a lot of my work
on classical Africa

00:05:29.490 --> 00:05:32.810
has been in Northeast
African corridor.

00:05:32.810 --> 00:05:36.290
And so the three classical
African civilizations

00:05:36.290 --> 00:05:39.610
are Kush, Nubia, and Kemet.

00:05:39.610 --> 00:05:41.230
People know Kemet as Egypt.

00:05:41.230 --> 00:05:42.750
But this is the Greek word.

00:05:42.750 --> 00:05:45.490
And there's no reason really to
use Greek words because we know

00:05:45.490 --> 00:05:48.220
the original word from
the hieroglyphic text.

00:05:48.220 --> 00:05:51.312
So we use the word classical
because it's more important

00:05:51.312 --> 00:05:53.100
if you use that
that than ancient.

00:05:53.100 --> 00:05:54.965
We here about classical
music, classical--

00:05:54.965 --> 00:06:00.750
what-- classical theater,
classical dance, classical art.

00:06:00.750 --> 00:06:02.994
So what does classical mean?

00:06:02.994 --> 00:06:05.160
Why would I put emphasis
on classical and not simply

00:06:05.160 --> 00:06:07.370
ancient.

00:06:07.370 --> 00:06:09.510
Even though ancient
civilization-- African

00:06:09.510 --> 00:06:12.090
civilization would be
technically correct,

00:06:12.090 --> 00:06:13.140
but what about classical?

00:06:13.140 --> 00:06:14.765
What does the term
actually mean?

00:06:14.765 --> 00:06:15.540
And we do here.

00:06:15.540 --> 00:06:16.490
We use it.

00:06:16.490 --> 00:06:18.390
We read about it.

00:06:18.390 --> 00:06:18.890
Anybody?

00:06:18.890 --> 00:06:19.580
Yes, sir.

00:06:19.580 --> 00:06:21.850
AUDIENCE: Maybe it
stood the test of time.

00:06:21.850 --> 00:06:22.410
It st--

00:06:22.410 --> 00:06:23.730
AUDIENCE: It stood
the test of time.

00:06:23.730 --> 00:06:24.920
MANU AMPIM: Stood
the test of time.

00:06:24.920 --> 00:06:25.545
You're correct.

00:06:25.545 --> 00:06:26.680
I like that.

00:06:26.680 --> 00:06:27.970
Anybody else?

00:06:27.970 --> 00:06:28.620
Yes, sir.

00:06:28.620 --> 00:06:30.056
AUDIENCE: It's still relevant.

00:06:30.056 --> 00:06:31.180
MANU AMPIM: Still relevant.

00:06:31.180 --> 00:06:32.610
Yes, absolutely.

00:06:32.610 --> 00:06:33.825
You both are correct.

00:06:33.825 --> 00:06:35.945
So when you say
classical, we mean

00:06:35.945 --> 00:06:38.465
anything that's the standard,
the model, the guide,

00:06:38.465 --> 00:06:40.239
the highest rank,
the highest class.

00:06:40.239 --> 00:06:41.530
As you've said, you're correct.

00:06:41.530 --> 00:06:45.360
Anything that has permanent
and lasting values.

00:06:45.360 --> 00:06:46.940
That's what's
meant by classical.

00:06:46.940 --> 00:06:49.730
That's why we call
these classical African

00:06:49.730 --> 00:06:51.220
civilizations.

00:06:51.220 --> 00:06:54.020
And the oldest of them is Kush.

00:06:54.020 --> 00:06:55.260
This a map of Kush.

00:06:55.260 --> 00:06:58.630
Kush is the area of
northeast Africa,

00:06:58.630 --> 00:07:00.960
but not only northeast
Africa, but across the Red

00:07:00.960 --> 00:07:03.590
Sea into Saudi Arabia and Yemen.

00:07:03.590 --> 00:07:07.130
All of this was a part of
the ancient Kushite empire.

00:07:07.130 --> 00:07:08.980
You can see it
here in the inset.

00:07:08.980 --> 00:07:10.020
That's the area.

00:07:10.020 --> 00:07:12.560
That's the oldest of
the civilizations.

00:07:12.560 --> 00:07:15.550
And Kush was based
in modern day Sudan.

00:07:15.550 --> 00:07:18.280
That's why I spend a
lot of time in the area.

00:07:18.280 --> 00:07:20.460
This is the area where
there's massive pyramids

00:07:20.460 --> 00:07:23.900
and elaborate temples and
great writing and science.

00:07:23.900 --> 00:07:25.800
And so most people are
not aware that there's

00:07:25.800 --> 00:07:29.750
twice as many pyramids in
Sudan as there is in Egypt.

00:07:29.750 --> 00:07:33.460
Civilization spread from south
to north, not the other way

00:07:33.460 --> 00:07:33.975
around.

00:07:33.975 --> 00:07:36.350
And so that's why I've done
extensive, firsthand research

00:07:36.350 --> 00:07:38.335
in order to document this.

00:07:38.335 --> 00:07:41.240
This is one statue
made out of granite.

00:07:41.240 --> 00:07:43.570
One of the powerful
Kushite kings.

00:07:43.570 --> 00:07:47.410
Can you imagine standing
under a 30 foot statue

00:07:47.410 --> 00:07:50.720
made by one of the most
powerful rulers of the time.

00:07:50.720 --> 00:07:52.380
So this is why I
spend so much time

00:07:52.380 --> 00:07:54.660
because the public,
in general, is not

00:07:54.660 --> 00:07:57.680
too familiar with these
powerful Kushite rulers.

00:07:57.680 --> 00:08:00.620
This is a 2,800 year
old statue here.

00:08:00.620 --> 00:08:02.810
And then, also,
some of you possibly

00:08:02.810 --> 00:08:06.070
could have seen this image here.

00:08:06.070 --> 00:08:09.130
Sometimes, people have it
on posters or handbags.

00:08:09.130 --> 00:08:12.520
If you go to the African
flea market in Berkeley,

00:08:12.520 --> 00:08:14.490
I've seen this
sometimes on t-shirts.

00:08:14.490 --> 00:08:17.240
But these are Kushite princes.

00:08:17.240 --> 00:08:22.720
And this is a 3,5000 year
old mural or drawing.

00:08:22.720 --> 00:08:24.590
And we know that they
are high stature,

00:08:24.590 --> 00:08:26.920
notice the crowns on their head.

00:08:26.920 --> 00:08:28.660
Notice the almond-shaped eyes.

00:08:28.660 --> 00:08:30.840
Notice the skin variation.

00:08:30.840 --> 00:08:33.360
Here it says in the
glyphs, it says Kush

00:08:33.360 --> 00:08:34.950
so we know where they're from.

00:08:34.950 --> 00:08:36.640
Notice the nice
jewelry, the sandals

00:08:36.640 --> 00:08:40.220
who you have the
attendant assisting.

00:08:40.220 --> 00:08:43.570
And here you have an assistant
with his arms outstretched.

00:08:43.570 --> 00:08:45.810
He has something
draped over this arm.

00:08:45.810 --> 00:08:49.370
What do you think this might
be that's draped over his arm

00:08:49.370 --> 00:08:49.870
here?

00:08:53.350 --> 00:08:53.850
OK.

00:08:53.850 --> 00:08:54.475
It's an animal.

00:08:54.475 --> 00:08:58.440
Yes, it's a leopard skin outfit
worn by priests and kings

00:08:58.440 --> 00:08:59.600
to what purpose?

00:08:59.600 --> 00:09:00.690
I'm glad you asked.

00:09:00.690 --> 00:09:03.220
For the purpose of
rituals and ceremonies.

00:09:03.220 --> 00:09:06.300
And then, the same
assistant is carrying--

00:09:06.300 --> 00:09:08.930
you see three rings,
here another three.

00:09:08.930 --> 00:09:11.475
And so three
indicates plurality.

00:09:11.475 --> 00:09:15.750
When something is pleural or
in abundance, you see three.

00:09:15.750 --> 00:09:17.870
So it means there's a
lot of whatever this is.

00:09:17.870 --> 00:09:20.232
Anybody have an idea
what this would be?

00:09:20.232 --> 00:09:23.040
What is the assistant carrying?

00:09:23.040 --> 00:09:25.735
AUDIENCE: A whole
lot of scrolls?

00:09:25.735 --> 00:09:26.360
MANU AMPIM: OK.

00:09:26.360 --> 00:09:27.120
Good try.

00:09:27.120 --> 00:09:28.026
Not exactly.

00:09:28.026 --> 00:09:29.900
Something a little more hard.

00:09:29.900 --> 00:09:31.110
AUDIENCE: Gold.

00:09:31.110 --> 00:09:32.280
MANU AMPIM: Gold.

00:09:32.280 --> 00:09:34.760
And there's currently,
right now in 2014,

00:09:34.760 --> 00:09:37.500
there's actually a
gold rush in Sudan now.

00:09:37.500 --> 00:09:39.430
Literally, there's
gold everywhere.

00:09:39.430 --> 00:09:43.700
In fact, the word Nubia-- the
root, nu or nub, it means gold.

00:09:43.700 --> 00:09:47.420
So Nubia, more likely than
not, means the land of gold.

00:09:47.420 --> 00:09:49.335
And now when you go
to Sudan, there's

00:09:49.335 --> 00:09:52.060
people panning for gold
everywhere literally.

00:09:52.060 --> 00:09:54.630
So anyway, if we had time,
we would talk about that.

00:09:54.630 --> 00:09:59.132
But really today, I want to
really talk about the third

00:09:59.132 --> 00:10:00.840
of these classical
African civilizations,

00:10:00.840 --> 00:10:05.110
which is actually listed
on the glyphs here.

00:10:05.110 --> 00:10:08.585
So let me point out what
glyphs I'm referring to.

00:10:08.585 --> 00:10:10.820
And it's these glyphs here.

00:10:10.820 --> 00:10:14.970
And this spelled Kemet, or
so called ancient Egypt.

00:10:14.970 --> 00:10:16.450
So this is what do you think?

00:10:19.050 --> 00:10:19.650
It's an owl.

00:10:19.650 --> 00:10:21.750
Yes, it represents the em sound.

00:10:21.750 --> 00:10:23.800
And this is a burnt
piece of charcoal.

00:10:23.800 --> 00:10:25.810
This is a half a loaf of bread.

00:10:25.810 --> 00:10:26.875
This is a crossroad.

00:10:26.875 --> 00:10:29.750
This is where-- it's the
locale where people lived.

00:10:29.750 --> 00:10:30.990
This the actual name.

00:10:30.990 --> 00:10:34.040
There's no such name as Egypt
until the Greeks come along

00:10:34.040 --> 00:10:34.740
much later.

00:10:34.740 --> 00:10:36.850
So many of the
African countries,

00:10:36.850 --> 00:10:39.130
these are not original
African names.

00:10:39.130 --> 00:10:41.240
So I just wanted
to point that out.

00:10:41.240 --> 00:10:43.895
And all right, let's
focus on writing

00:10:43.895 --> 00:10:46.680
before we deal with more
of the hard sciences here.

00:10:46.680 --> 00:10:53.770
African contributions in the
field of writing most of us--

00:10:53.770 --> 00:10:55.960
Most of us are not
always necessarily

00:10:55.960 --> 00:11:00.830
familiar with the source of
what we have in front of us

00:11:00.830 --> 00:11:02.910
on a regular basis, paper.

00:11:02.910 --> 00:11:04.385
So this is actual papyrus plant.

00:11:04.385 --> 00:11:05.980
It grows in marshes.

00:11:05.980 --> 00:11:08.960
So they would take
the papyrus plant.

00:11:08.960 --> 00:11:10.950
And then, they would
cut it into strips.

00:11:10.950 --> 00:11:13.210
And then, they would
eventually make paper.

00:11:13.210 --> 00:11:16.530
So from papyrus, we
get the word paper.

00:11:16.530 --> 00:11:18.195
And this is an
important contribution.

00:11:18.195 --> 00:11:21.050
This is some of the
writing, the text here.

00:11:21.050 --> 00:11:23.340
You always read the
text from top to bottom.

00:11:23.340 --> 00:11:26.800
This is text inside a pyramid,
so people call it pyramid text.

00:11:26.800 --> 00:11:29.150
And even without ever
studying the language,

00:11:29.150 --> 00:11:33.250
I bet that most of you can
figure out some of these images

00:11:33.250 --> 00:11:36.580
without ever having taken any
class or seminar or training.

00:11:36.580 --> 00:11:39.970
So for example, this
